Seeing you do stuff with baking soda and vinegar makes me want to see your take on sodium acetate, AKA hot ice. It's the salt formed by mixing baking soda and vinegar, and because the trihydrate form melts below the boiling point of water mixed with it, you can make a supersaturated solution of it by boiling off the water and cooling it with a lid to prevent any more water from evaporating. Then, you just provide a nucleation site by dropping in a sodium acetate crystal (or a tiny bit of baking soda, if it's your first batch), and it crystallizes quickly. The pure crystals are white and look like ice; between that and the fact that the crystallization is exothermic, you get the name hot ice. (Unfortunately, grocery store vinegar isn't 100% pure water and acetic acid, so it tends to come out a bit yellowish.) You can also get purer sodium acetate trihydrate by cutting open certain types of heating packs.
EDIT: Sorry, if you make it from scratch, your studio will absolutely smell like vinegar. OTOH, the sodium acetate itself smells kinda like pretzels.
